<subSubSection id="C37E6539FFDCF504FF82EDB5A90CFAE2" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BDB36B2FFDCF504FF82EDB5A90CFAE2" blockId="1.[113,753,491,1348]" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">
<emphasis id="B910EAA0FFDCF504FF82EDB5A967FDA5" box="[113,514,491,515]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">
<emphasis id="B910EAA0FFDCF504FF82EDB5AAE7FDA5" bold="true" box="[113,386,491,515]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">Differential diagnosis. –</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C644D31FFDCF504FE7EEDB2A967FDA5" authorityName="Waterhouse" authorityYear="1879" box="[397,514,492,515]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Metanoeus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Metanoeus</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
is defined mainly by the presence of the unique very obtuse pronotal carinae (Fig. 2), extremely long lamellae of male antennae (Fig. 3), and vestigial valvifers in the ovipositor. The genus resembles the related 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D31FFDCF504FF03EE2FA978FD2E" authority="Waterhouse, 1879" authorityName="Waterhouse" authorityYear="1879" box="[240,541,625,648]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Cautires" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B910EAA0FFDCF504FF03EE2FAA29FD2E" box="[240,332,625,648]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">Cautires</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFF54B43FFDCF504FEA5EE2FA978FD2E" author="Waterhouse, C" box="[342,541,625,648]" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" refId="ref6186" refString="Waterhouse, C. O., 1879. Illustrations of the Typical Specimens of Coleoptera in the Collection of the British Museum. Part I. Lycidae. British Museum, London. 93 pp." type="book" year="1879">
Waterhouse, 
<quantity id="4C9C9B57FFDCF504FE14EE2FA978FD2E" box="[487,541,625,648]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.77266" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" unit="in" value="1879.0">1879</quantity>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
in the presence of nine longitudinal costae on each elytron, but these genera differ in the structure of the pronotal carinae and especially in the structure of male genitalia. Unlike the very diverse shape of the phallus in 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D31FFDCF504FE8FEEA9AA97FCA8" authorityName="Waterhouse" authorityYear="1879" box="[380,498,759,782]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Metanoeus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B910EAA0FFDCF504FE8FEEA9AA97FCA8" box="[380,498,759,782]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">Metanoeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Figs. 5–16), 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D31FFDCF504FD67EEA9A995FCA8" authorityName="Waterhouse" authorityYear="1879" box="[660,752,759,782]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Cautires" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B910EAA0FFDCF504FD67EEA9A995FCA8" box="[660,752,759,782]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">Cautires</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have, as a rule, a very slender, simple phallus with only two small thorns in the internal sac (
<bibRefCitation id="EFF54B43FFDCF504FE36EF67A937FCF6" author="Bocak, L" box="[453,594,825,848]" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" pagination="315 - 351" refId="ref5427" refString="Bocak, L., 2002. Generic revision and phylogenetic analysis of the Metriorrhynchinae (Coleoptera: Lycidae). European Journal of Entomology, 99: 315 - 351." type="journal article" year="2002">Bocak, 2002</bibRefCitation>
). Another very species-rich metriorrhynchine genus, 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D31FFDCF504FE0BEF05ABCCFC35" authority="Waterhouse, 1879" authorityName="Waterhouse" authorityYear="1879" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Xylobanus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B910EAA0FFDCF504FE0BEF05A902FCD4" box="[504,615,859,882]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">Xylobanus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFF54B43FFDCF504FD9FEF04ABCCFC35" author="Waterhouse, C" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" refId="ref6186" refString="Waterhouse, C. O., 1879. Illustrations of the Typical Specimens of Coleoptera in the Collection of the British Museum. Part I. Lycidae. British Museum, London. 93 pp." type="book" year="1879">Waterhouse, 1879</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, differs in four longitudinal costae on each elytron. The last Oriental genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D31FFDCF504FEC9EFC3A902FC12" authority="Waterhouse, 1879" authorityName="Waterhouse" authorityYear="1879" box="[314,615,925,948]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Bulenides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B910EAA0FFDCF504FEC9EFC3AAC7FC12" box="[314,418,925,948]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">Bulenides</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFF54B43FFDCF504FE5BEFC3A902FC12" author="Waterhouse, C" box="[424,615,925,948]" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" refId="ref6186" refString="Waterhouse, C. O., 1879. Illustrations of the Typical Specimens of Coleoptera in the Collection of the British Museum. Part I. Lycidae. British Museum, London. 93 pp." type="book" year="1879">Waterhouse, 1879</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
was recently synonymized with 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D31FFDCF504FECFEFE1A9D8FC73" authority="(Dudkova &amp; Bocak, 2010)" baseAuthorityName="Dudkova &amp; Bocak" baseAuthorityYear="2010" box="[316,701,958,982]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Cautires" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B910EAA0FFDCF504FECFEFE1AAF2FC70" box="[316,407,959,982]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">Cautires</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFF54B43FFDCF504FE56EFE0A9D0FC73" author="Dudkova, P" box="[421,693,958,981]" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" pagination="28 - 48" refId="ref5779" refString="Dudkova, P. &amp; L. Bocak, 2010. A review of the Cautires obsoletus species group from Indo-Burma (Coleoptera: Lycidae). Zootaxa, 2527: 28 - 48." type="journal article" year="2010">Dudkova &amp; Bocak, 2010</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. The given characters enable reliable identification of both sexes in the Oriental region. Similar obtuse carinae were found in some 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D31FFDCF504FF5DE87DABCCFBFD" authority="Gemminger &amp; Gemminger et Harold, 1869" authorityName="Gemminger &amp; Gemminger et Harold" authorityYear="1869" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Metriorrhynchus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B910EAA0FFDCF504FF5DE87DAA04FB9C" box="[174,353,1059,1082]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">Metriorrhynchus</emphasis>
Gemminger &amp; Gemminger et Harold, 1869
</taxonomicName>
, which differs in the larger body, long slender phallus, only slightly shortened valvifers, and serrate male antennae or much shorter lamellae in some Papuan species (
<bibRefCitation id="EFF54B43FFDCF504FD57E8D8ABCEFB19" author="Bocak, L" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" pagination="253 - 260" refId="ref5459" refString="Bocak, L., 2007. A revision of Metriorrhynchus (Coleoptera: Lycidae) from the Greater Sunda Islands and continental Asia. Raffles Bulletin of Zoology, 55: 253 - 260." type="journal article" year="2007">Bocak, 2007</bibRefCitation>
). Some characters reported for 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D31FFDCF504FE0AE8F6A90BFB19" authorityName="Waterhouse" authorityYear="1879" box="[505,622,1192,1215]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Metanoeus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B910EAA0FFDCF504FE0AE8F6A90BFB19" box="[505,622,1192,1215]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">Metanoeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, such as the sclerotization of the vagina, long processes of scutellum and long, basally attached male antennal lamellae, remind of some Papuan representatives of 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D31FFDCF504FE3EE952A9EDFA85" authorityName="Kleine" authorityYear="1926" box="[461,648,1292,1315]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Metriorrhynchini">Metriorrhynchini</taxonomicName>
, but none of these occurs sympatrically with 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D31FFDCF504FE1EE973A907FAE2" authorityName="Waterhouse" authorityYear="1879" box="[493,610,1325,1348]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Metanoeus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B910EAA0FFDCF504FE1EE973A907FAE2" box="[493,610,1325,1348]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">Metanoeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C37E6539FFDCF504FF82E931AF0FFA21" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BDB36B2FFDCF504FF82E931AECFFEBF" blockId="1.[113,753,1391,2048]" lastBlockId="1.[813,1452,192,281]" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">
<emphasis id="B910EAA0FFDCF504FF82E931AA43FA21" bold="true" box="[113,294,1391,1415]" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">
<emphasis id="B910EAA0FFDCF504FF82E931AA6AFA21" bold="true" box="[113,271,1391,1415]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">Redescription.</emphasis>
–
</emphasis>
Body small to medium sized, 
<quantity id="4C9C9B57FFDCF504FD73E92EA989FA21" box="[640,748,1392,1415]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" metricValueMax="1.8" metricValueMin="0.6" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" unit="mm" value="12.0" valueMax="18.0" valueMin="6.0">6–18 mm</quantity>
, weakly sclerotized, dorso-ventrally flattened (Fig. 1). Colouration variable, most species uniformly yellow dorsally in the 
<collectingCountry id="F3737622FFDCF504FF4EE98AAA5EFA4D" box="[189,315,1492,1515]" name="Philippines" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">Philippines</collectingCountry>
, variably coloured in the Great Sunda Islands and continental Asia. Head small, partly hidden by pronotum, without rostrum, with large eyes in both sexes. Male antennal lamellae long, attached to bases of antennomeres, slender basally, female antennae serrate (Fig. 4). Maxillary palpi 4-segmented, slender, apical palpomere parallel-sided, labial palpi 3-segmented, similar in shape. Pronotum with seven areolae, carinae obtuse (Fig. 2). Scutellum deeply emarginate at apex. Elytra parallel-sided to slightly widened backward, each with nine longitudinal costae, four of them stronger, intermediate costae weak. Male genitalia with phallus and phallobase, parameres absent. Phallobase small, phallobasal membrane extensive, at least partly sclerotized. Phallus variable in shape, often considerably shortened (Figs. 5–16). Internal sac with three pairs of thorns or only partly sclerotized membranous structures. Female genitalia short, with plate-shaped coxites and short valvifers modified into small plates; vagina often considerably sclerotized; spermaduct usually extremely long, in species with membranous vagina shorter (
<bibRefCitation id="EFF54B43FFDCF504FAE3ED5CAEFBFEBF" author="Bocak, L" box="[1296,1438,258,281]" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" pagination="315 - 351" refId="ref5427" refString="Bocak, L., 2002. Generic revision and phylogenetic analysis of the Metriorrhynchinae (Coleoptera: Lycidae). European Journal of Entomology, 99: 315 - 351." type="journal article" year="2002">Bocak, 2002</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BDB36B2FFDCF504FCDEED1BA8ABFC35" blockId="1.[813,1452,325,915]" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">
<emphasis id="B910EAA0FFDCF504FCDEED1BAF93FEFB" bold="true" box="[813,1270,325,349]" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">
<emphasis id="B910EAA0FFDCF504FCDEED1BAF86FEFB" bold="true" box="[813,1251,325,349]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">Diversity, distribution and conservation.</emphasis>
–
</emphasis>
There have been described only 23 species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D31FFDCF504FB8EED39AEC2FEDB" authority="(Kleine, 1933)" baseAuthorityName="Kleine" baseAuthorityYear="1933" box="[1149,1447,358,382]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Metanoeus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B910EAA0FFDCF504FB8EED39AF90FED8" box="[1149,1269,359,382]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">Metanoeus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFF54B43FFDCF504FAFBED38AEC5FEDB" author="Kleine, R" box="[1288,1440,358,381]" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" pagination="1 - 145" refId="ref5944" refString="Kleine, R., 1933. Lycidae. Pars 128. In: Junk, W. &amp; S. Schenkling (eds.), Coleopterorum Catalogus. W. Junk, Berlin. Pp. 1 - 145." type="book chapter" year="1933">Kleine, 1933</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. All species were reported from the tropical rain forests in the Great Sundas, Peninsular 
<collectingCountry id="F3737622FFDCF504FB69EDF7AE65FE66" box="[1178,1280,425,448]" name="Malaysia" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">Malaysia</collectingCountry>
, Indochina and the 
<collectingCountry id="F3737622FFDCF504FCAAED94A8B3FE47" box="[857,982,458,481]" name="Philippines" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">Philippines</collectingCountry>
and no record is available outside these regions. The highest diversity of 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D31FFDCF504FB6CEDB2AE71FDA5" baseAuthorityName="Kleine" baseAuthorityYear="1933" box="[1183,1300,492,515]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Metanoeus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B910EAA0FFDCF504FB6CEDB2AE71FDA5" box="[1183,1300,492,515]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">Metanoeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was reported from northeastern Borneo and Sumatra. Concerning the distribution and diversity of 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D31FFDCF504FB71EE71AF98FDE0" baseAuthorityName="Kleine" baseAuthorityYear="1933" box="[1154,1277,559,582]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Metanoeus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B910EAA0FFDCF504FB71EE71AF98FDE0" box="[1154,1277,559,582]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">Metanoeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
throughout its range, we may consider the Philippine 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D31FFDCF504FB25EE0EAE2EFDC1" baseAuthorityName="Kleine" baseAuthorityYear="1933" box="[1238,1355,592,615]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Metanoeus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B910EAA0FFDCF504FB25EE0EAE2EFDC1" box="[1238,1355,592,615]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">Metanoeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
fauna to be a result of dispersal from the Sundaland. The Huxley‘s line separating the 
<collectingCountry id="F3737622FFDCF504FBE3EECCAFEAFD0F" box="[1040,1167,658,681]" name="Philippines" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">Philippines</collectingCountry>
and the Oriental region represents a valid zoogeographical border for several lycid genera such as 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D31FFDCF504FC38EE8BAF8AFD4A" authority="Kleine, 1926" authorityName="Kleine" authorityYear="1926" box="[971,1263,725,748]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Cautiromimus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B910EAA0FFDCF504FC38EE8BAF06FD4A" box="[971,1123,725,748]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">Cautiromimus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFF54B43FFDCF504FB94EE8BAF8AFD4A" author="Kleine, R" box="[1127,1263,725,748]" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" pagination="33 - 81" refId="ref5920" refString="Kleine, R., 1926. Die Lyciden der Philippinen-Inseln. The Philippine Journal of Science, 31: 33 - 81." type="journal article" year="1926">Kleine, 1926</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
or species groups of 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D31FFDCF504FCBCEEA9AF6EFCA8" authorityName="Gemminger &amp; Gemminger et Harold" authorityYear="1869" box="[847,1035,759,782]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Metriorrhynchus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B910EAA0FFDCF504FCBCEEA9AF6EFCA8" box="[847,1035,759,782]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">Metriorrhynchus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and many other animals (Brown &amp; Guttman, 2002), but some genera, such as 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D31FFDCF504FAE7EF46AEEEFC89" baseAuthorityName="Kleine" baseAuthorityYear="1933" box="[1300,1419,792,815]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Metanoeus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B910EAA0FFDCF504FAE7EF46AEEEFC89" box="[1300,1419,792,815]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">Metanoeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D31FFDCF504FCDEEF67A8EDFCF6" baseAuthorityName="Dudkova &amp; Bocak" baseAuthorityYear="2010" box="[813,904,825,848]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Cautires" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B910EAA0FFDCF504FCDEEF67A8EDFCF6" box="[813,904,825,848]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">Cautires</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, are known from the 
<collectingCountry id="F3737622FFDCF504FB87EF67AF89FCF6" box="[1140,1260,825,848]" name="Philippines" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">Philippines</collectingCountry>
and do not occur beyond the Wallace line in Sulawesi and further to the East (
<bibRefCitation id="EFF54B43FFDCF504FCC7EF22A8A7FC35" author="Bocak, L" box="[820,962,892,915]" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" pagination="315 - 351" refId="ref5427" refString="Bocak, L., 2002. Generic revision and phylogenetic analysis of the Metriorrhynchinae (Coleoptera: Lycidae). European Journal of Entomology, 99: 315 - 351." type="journal article" year="2002">Bocak, 2002</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BDB36B2FFDCF504FCDEEFE0AF0FFA21" blockId="1.[813,1452,958,1415]" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">
The lower montane forests habitats typical for 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D31FFDCF504FAE5EFE1AEEEFC70" baseAuthorityName="Kleine" baseAuthorityYear="1933" box="[1302,1419,959,982]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Metanoeus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B910EAA0FFDCF504FAE5EFE1AEEEFC70" box="[1302,1419,959,982]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">Metanoeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
lie in the most densely populated regions of Java, Sumatra, and the 
<collectingCountry id="F3737622FFDCF504FCA6E85FA8A8FBBE" box="[853,973,1025,1048]" name="Philippines" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">Philippines</collectingCountry>
and are highly endangered by deforestation. Especially, the fauna of the 
<collectingCountry id="F3737622FFDCF504FB9CE87CAF8FFB9F" box="[1135,1258,1058,1081]" name="Philippines" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">Philippines</collectingCountry>
may be strongly damaged by the ongoing loss of habitats. The results show, that many previously described taxa were typologically defined on the basis of a few specimens and they represent in fact complexes of highly similar and often distantly related species occurring in small ranges. The extraordinary biodiversity of the 
<collectingCountry id="F3737622FFDCF504FBE0E8B4AFF1FAA7" box="[1043,1172,1258,1281]" name="Philippines" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">Philippines</collectingCountry>
is known also in other groups of animals and the archipelago is considered as one of the biodiversity hotspots (
<bibRefCitation id="EFF54B43FFDCF504FB82E973AE23FAE2" author="Myers, N &amp; Mittermeier, C &amp; Mittermeier, G" box="[1137,1350,1325,1348]" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" pagination="853 - 858" refId="ref6027" refString="Myers, N., R. A. Mittermeier, C. G. Mittermeier, G. A. B. da Fonseca, &amp; J. Kent, 2000. Biodiversity hotspots for conservation priorities. Nature, 403: 853 - 858." type="journal article" year="2000">Myers et al., 2000</bibRefCitation>
). Further deforestation may quickly lead to substantial loss of the diversity (
<bibRefCitation id="EFF54B43FFDCF504FC6AE92EAF3AFA21" author="Sodhi, N &amp; Koh, B" box="[921,1119,1392,1415]" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" pagination="654 - 660" refId="ref6092" refString="Sodhi, N. S., L. P. Koh, B. W. Brook, &amp; P. K. L. Ng, 2004. Southeast Asian biodiversity: An impending disaster. Trends in Ecology and Evolution, 19: 654 - 660." type="journal article" year="2004">Sodhi et al., 2004</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C37E6539FFDCF507FCDEE9ECAFBBF7E7" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="165" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="8BDB36B2FFDCF504FCDEE9ECAFC3F879" blockId="1.[813,1452,1458,2015]" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">
<emphasis id="B910EAA0FFDCF504FCDEE9ECAF41FA6C" box="[813,1060,1458,1482]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">
<emphasis id="B910EAA0FFDCF504FCDEE9ECA8C4FA6C" bold="true" box="[813,929,1458,1482]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">Biology. –</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C644D31FFDCF504FC5FE9EDAF41FA6C" baseAuthorityName="Kleine" baseAuthorityYear="1933" box="[940,1060,1459,1482]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Metanoeus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Metanoeus</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
occurs from lowlands to montane forests and larvae live in decaying moist wood in the final stage of decomposition. The larva of one Bornean species was described by Bocak &amp; Matsuda (2003). The recent observation showed similar biology also in 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D31FFDCF504FAA1EA66A884F9D6" authority="Bourgeois, 1879" authorityName="Bourgeois" authorityYear="1879" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Plateros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B910EAA0FFDCF504FAA1EA66AECEF9E9" box="[1362,1451,1592,1615]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">Plateros</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFF54B43FFDCF504FCDEEA07A884F9D6" author="Bourgeois, J" box="[813,993,1625,1648]" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" pagination="15 - 19" refId="ref5659" refString="Bourgeois, J., 1879. Lycides recueillis au Bresil par C. Van Volxem. Annales de la Societe entomologique de Belgique, 22: 15 - 19." type="journal article" year="1879">Bourgeois, 1879</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D31FFDCF504FC1FEA07AF22F9D6" baseAuthorityName="Dudkova &amp; Bocak" baseAuthorityYear="2010" box="[1004,1095,1625,1648]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Cautires" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B910EAA0FFDCF504FC1FEA07AF22F9D6" box="[1004,1095,1625,1648]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">Cautires</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D31FFDCF504FB77EA07A8A1F937" authority="(Levkanicova &amp; Bocak, 2009)" baseAuthorityName="Levkanicova &amp; Bocak" baseAuthorityYear="2009" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Xylobanus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B910EAA0FFDCF504FB77EA07AF90F9D6" box="[1156,1269,1625,1648]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">Xylobanus</emphasis>
(Levkanicova &amp; Bocak, 2009)
</taxonomicName>
. Most adults of the Philippine species were collected by general sweeping of lower undergrowth of the tropical rain forest where they slowly move or sit on leaves. Although males of some species have extraordinary large eyes, which usually indicates a nocturnal activity, 
<taxonomicName id="4C644D31FFDCF504FAC4EB5EAECEF8B1" baseAuthorityName="Kleine" baseAuthorityYear="1933" box="[1335,1451,1792,1815]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Metanoeus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B910EAA0FFDCF504FAC4EB5EAECEF8B1" box="[1335,1451,1792,1815]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="164">Metanoeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are only seldom collected at light. The bright coloration of adults is regularly shared with unrelated syntopically occurring species from various lycid genera and may have a warning function as all lycids are unprofitable to predators due to the content of bitter and smelling compounds (
<bibRefCitation id="EFF54B43FFDCF504FA95EBF8A8CCF879" author="Eisner, T &amp; Schroeder, N &amp; Snyder, J &amp; Grant, D &amp; Aneshansley, D &amp; Utterback, J" pageId="1" pageNumber="164" pagination="109 - 119" refId="ref5814" refString="Eisner, T., F. C. Schroeder, N. Snyder, J. B. Grant, D. J. Aneshansley, D. Utterback, J. Meinwald, &amp; M. Eisner, 2008. Defensive chemistry of lycid beetles and of mimetic cerambycid beetles that feed on them. Chemoecology, 18: 109 - 119." type="journal article" year="2008">Eisner et al., 2008</bibRefCitation>
; Bocak &amp; Yagi, 2010).
</paragraph>
